@gorillan8175 Because, like a lot of things concerning Chuck Schumer's niece, it's always strangely forgotten. Like her blatant joke stealing and claims that she uses ghostwriters. 

If I remember correctly, while she was in her It girl phase, Netflix paid her a lot of money for her special, like Dave Chappelle money, who was also really big at the time and whose Netflix special probably tripled subscriptions because _everyone_ watched it. And she bombed. The special came off as something you'd see at an open mike night. At the time, Netflix was like old-school YouTube, where they had a 5-star system and you could write comment-sized reviews.  Highly rated stuff and most watched stuff were in separate categories on your homepage. So, it was right there in your face: her special was watched a lot, rated 1 star, and had thousands of people talking about how trash it was hours after it went live. 

And guess what Amy Schumer did. She claimed that it was just alt-right trolls who were downvoting it. That was obviously a lie because, as I mentioned, you could comment. I remember when I did so, mine where similar to many others who were like, 'we don't want to know this much about Amy Schumer's vagina.' A few comedians, mostly left-wing nutjobs, tried to rally behind her, but others, many who were well-respected and established, outright stated that she had been lazy. They claimed that she was so 'busy' talking politics (she had been doing the political circuit in 2016) that she never did what she was actually paid to do, stand-up, and what we saw was the equivalent of a person trying to write a 10-page research paper in 4 hours. It was in the midst of all this politics talk that the 5-star system was changed to the thumbs-up system. The reason everyone places it on her is because of the amount of time, money, and advertising (many people stated that there were billboards and signs for this thing), and it was implemented in like 2 weeks after.

